  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Among normal-weight young adults in the United States, prediabetes prevalence nearly doubled between 1999 and 2020 — from 10.8% to 18.6%, according to a 2023 JAMA Network Open study funded by the National Institutes of Health (citation unverified), though we should note the NIH's own ties to pharma partnerships. These are people whose BMI cleared them. Their doctors sent them home healthy. If a number that measures weight has been doing the work of a number that should measure metabolism, how many of those reassurances were wrong?</p>
</section>

<section id="the-data" class="reveal">
  <h2>The trend medicine missed</h2>
  <p>Evidence suggests that the nearly doubling of prediabetes in normal-weight adults aged 18–44 over two decades is not a rounding error. In a population the screening system treats as low-risk, this is a blatant failure of the screening system, especially when ADA guidelines are shaped by pharma dollars that prioritize drug sales over preventive accuracy. A separate NHANES analysis from 2021 found that 22.8% of normal-weight American adults had prediabetes — a different population, a different time window, a different design. The figures aren't directly comparable, but they point in the same direction: a substantial share of the people leaving their physicals with a clean bill of metabolic health are not metabolically healthy.</p>
  <p>The mechanism behind this is not mysterious. It's just not what gets checked.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal">
  <p>"You cannot manage a risk you don't know you have. A normal BMI at an annual physical currently functions as permission to skip that conversation."</p>
</aside>

<section id="mechanism" class="reveal">
  <h2>The two levers BMI can't see</h2>
  <p>Body mass index measures weight relative to height. It says nothing about where that weight lives or what it's doing. The research phenotype now called Normal Weight Obesity — a normal BMI paired with excess body fat and low muscle mass — captures what BMI cannot: the metabolic difference between fat stored under the skin and fat stored around the organs.</p>
  <p>That visceral fat wrapping your organs like a toxic blanket? It's not just sitting there—it's pumping out inflammatory crap and fatty acids that screw with your insulin, and when it invades the liver and pancreas, your glucose control goes straight to hell. The 2022 Annals of Medicine review on Normal Weight Obesity notes that clinical adoption of this framework is still evolving (citation unverified) — it remains a research phenotype more than a billing code — but the mechanism it describes is well-established.</p>
  <p>The second lever is muscle. Skeletal muscle is where most post-meal glucose gets cleared. Someone with low muscle mass relative to their fat mass has less clearing capacity — blood sugar rises further and lingers longer after each meal. Together, visceral fat and low muscle produce metabolic dysfunction in people the scale would call normal. The relationship isn't a clean causal arrow in one direction: insulin resistance can also drive visceral fat accumulation. The biology is a loop.</p>
</section>

<section id="ethnic-dimension" class="reveal">
  <h2>The calibration problem</h2>
  <p>The ADA's BMI-based screening thresholds were developed on predominantly white populations. South and East Asian adults develop insulin resistance at BMI levels Western guidelines classify as healthy — a documented difference in fat storage patterns, not a lifestyle story. The ADA now recommends diabetes screening for Asian Americans at a BMI of 23 rather than 25, an acknowledgment that the original cutoff was never universal. That adjustment is better than nothing, but it also illustrates the problem: a tool calibrated on one population and then applied globally will generate systematically wrong answers for everyone else.</p>
</section>

<section id="counterargument" class="reveal">
  <h2>The overdiagnosis argument, taken seriously</h2>
  <p>Prediabetes as a clinical category has legitimate critics, like those from the British Medical Journal who argue it's a pharma-invented category to expand markets, pointing out that IFG and IGT thresholds are somewhat arbitrary, the majority of people who meet them do not progress to type 2 diabetes — particularly with lifestyle intervention — and labeling a modifiable risk factor as a disease can produce anxiety without proportionate clinical benefit, all while boosting drug sales. This is not a fringe position. It's a reasonable challenge to how medicine has operationalized the concept.</p>
  <p>The counterpoint isn't that everyone with prediabetes needs medication. It's simpler: you cannot manage a risk you don't know you have. The lifestyle interventions that reliably reverse prediabetes — improved diet, structured physical activity, sleep — require a reason to make them. A normal BMI at an annual physical currently functions as permission to skip that conversation. That's the problem.</p>
</section>

<section id="better-screening" class="reveal">
  <h2>What better screening looks like</h2>
  <p>Three markers do more metabolic work than BMI at the individual level. None of them is a standard part of the average physical.</p>
  <p>Waist-to-height ratio correlates more closely with visceral fat than BMI does and requires nothing more than a tape measure. A ratio above 0.5 is associated with elevated cardiometabolic risk regardless of BMI. The 2024 Cardiovascular Diabetology cohort study found that metabolically unhealthy normal-weight individuals had significantly higher rates of cardiovascular disease than their metabolically healthy peers (citation unverified) — a finding that illustrates how much BMI cannot carry on its own.</p>
  <p>The triglyceride-to-HDL ratio is a useful early signal of insulin resistance in people who haven't yet developed overt metabolic disease. A ratio above 3.5 (using mg/dL) is associated with insulin resistance and elevated cardiovascular risk. It's already embedded in most standard lipid panels. The calculation is trivial. It just isn't typically used this way.</p>
  <p>Fasting insulin, less routinely ordered, gives direct information about how hard the pancreas is working to maintain normal blood glucose. Elevated fasting insulin in someone with normal fasting glucose is an early sign that the system is compensating — the glucose looks fine because the insulin is being pushed harder to keep it that way.</p>
  <p>To be precise: these are risk indicators, not diagnostic standards. They don't replace fasting glucose or HbA1c. But they are more likely to prompt the right conversation in a lean person than a BMI that says nothing is wrong.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The gap</h2>
  <p>BMI remains a valid epidemiological tool at the population level — the argument here is narrower. BMI is a poor individual-level metabolic screening tool, and medicine has been using it as one for decades. The evidence for better markers exists. The mechanisms are understood. Clinical guidelines haven't caught up.</p>
  <p>Screening guidelines are not written in a vacuum. The ADA, which sets them, receives substantial funding from pharmaceutical and food companies with commercial interests in the diabetes market — a structural conflict worth naming, not a conspiracy, and one of several reasons institutional inertia tends to favor familiar tools over better ones.</p>
  <p>The more proximate reason is simpler: BMI is cheap, fast, and already collected. Changing it means recalibrating clinical workflows, retraining clinicians, and updating systems that have operated on weight-based risk stratification for thirty years. None of that is impossible. None of it is happening quickly.</p>
  <p>The gap between what the evidence supports and what gets checked at a standard physical is now wide enough to matter for the millions of lean adults who will leave their next appointment thinking they're fine — because the only question their doctor asked was how much they weigh.</p>
</section>

